Object Oriented Programming (OOP)

OOP in R

Central to any object-oriented language are the concepts of class and of methods. A class is a definition of an object. Typically a class contains several slots that are used to hold class specific information. An object in the language must be an instance of some class. Programming is based on objects or instances of classes.

Computations are carried out via methods. Methods are basically functions that are specialized to carry out specific calculations on objects, usually of a specific class. This is what makes the language object oriented. In R, generic functions are used to determine the appropriate method. The generic function is responsible for determining the class of its argument(s) and uses that information to select the appropriate method.

Source: R Language Definition, version 3.2.1, R Core Team

List of generic functions()

print()
summary()
plot()

OOP Systems in R

  • R has three object oriented systems (plus the base types)
  • Central to any OO system are the concepts of class and method
  • A class defines the behavior of objects by describing their attributes and their relationship to other classes
  • The class is also used when selecting methods, functions that behave differently depending on the class of their input

Rs three OO Systems

  • S3
  • S4
  • RC

Source: Advanced R, Hadley Wickham, CRC Press

S Languange

S3 & S4 are based on the Evolution of the S Language

Evolution of S Languange, 4 major milestones

  1. Object types, a set of internal types defined in the C implementation, and originally called modes in S;
  2. Vector structures, defined by the concept of vectors (indexable objects) with added structure defined by attributes;
  3. S3 classes, that is, objects with class attributes and corresponding one-argument method dispatch, but without class definitions;
  4. Formal classes with class definitions, and corresponding generic functions and general methods, usually called S4 classes and methods in R.

Source Software for Data Analysis; Programming with R by John M. Chambers

S3 is Rs first and simplist OO System

S3

Most functions in Base R are s3. Examples:

?plot()

To get insight into the available method for each class (Needs to be a geneirc function)

methods(plot)

The functions print() and summary() are two other well known generic functions.

Then to see the function code based on the class we can use:

getS3method(plot)

A data.frame is an example of a S3 Object

The only way to check, within Base R, if an object is S3 is if the below code returns TRUE

is.object() & !isS4

Example S3 object

df <- data.frame(A = 1:20,
                 B = runif(20) + (1:20))
is.object(df) & !isS4(df)
## [1] TRUE

S4

For S4, we can easily check if they are S4 via isS4()

RStudio also captures this by stating the object as Formal Class

When we look at the structure within RStudio via the Environment tab, we see @ slots.

Which brings us to the most important aspect that requires understanding -> extracting information of s4 Objects:

@ or slot() can be used to extract a particular part of the object, similar to $ and [[ for S3 objects

Take the following example:

library("Matrix")
M2 <- toeplitz(as(c(1,.5, rep(0,12), -.1), "sparseVector"))
c2 <- chol(M2)
isS4(M2)
## [1] TRUE
isS4(c2)
## [1] TRUE

Apply Family

The Family of Apply Functions

The apply family of functions are one of the great powers of R. In most cases they are a replacement of using loops in R. A solid understanding of the apply functions is highly recommended.

Below a short summary will be given on the main apply functions.

List of Apply functions:

apply()
lapply()
sapply()
tapply()
mapply()
eapply()
rapply()
vapply()

Dummy Data Set

Here we create a Dummy Data Set:

First step is the dates vector:

A <- Sys.Date()+1:500

Then take out all days that are not weekdays from the vector

week <- c("Monday","Tuesday","Wednesday","Thursday","Friday")
MD <- A[weekdays(A) %in% week]

Daily Vol numbers:

Vol_HS <- 0.2/sqrt(252)
Vol_CSI <- 0.4/sqrt(252)
Vol_STI <- 0.12/sqrt(252)
Vol_N225 <- 0.25/sqrt(252)

Final Data frame

set.seed(12345)
df <- data.frame(Date = MD,
                 HS   = rnorm(length(MD),sd=Vol_HS),
                 CSI  = rnorm(length(MD),sd=Vol_CSI),
                 STI  = rnorm(length(MD),sd=Vol_STI),
                 N225 = rnorm(length(MD),sd=Vol_N225))

tapply()

df$Year <- factor(format(df$Date,'%Y'))
tapply(df[,"HS"],df$Year,sd)
##       2017       2018 
## 0.01401209 0.01241014

As tapply only works on vectors, we need to use one more apply function to get the results for all columns

apply(df[,2:5],2,function(x) tapply(x,df$Year,sd))
##              HS        CSI         STI       N225
## 2017 0.01401209 0.02288498 0.007257507 0.01605129
## 2018 0.01241014 0.02584105 0.007239914 0.01591130

lapply()

A simple example:

A_list <- list(A = 1:10,
               B = 11:20,
               C = 21:30,
               D = 31:40)
lapply(A_list,mean)
## $A
## [1] 5.5
## 
## $B
## [1] 15.5
## 
## $C
## [1] 25.5
## 
## $D
## [1] 35.5

Note the outcome is a list with the same length as the input

If the outcome can be simplified then using sapply produces a desirable outcome

sapply(A_list,mean)
##    A    B    C    D 
##  5.5 15.5 25.5 35.5

Note that is important to understand the benefits of Data Frames and lists

df_l <- list(HS   = df[,c(1,2)],
             CSI  = df[,c(1,3)],
             STI  = df[,c(1,4)],
             N225 = df[,c(1,5)])
sapply(df_l, function(x) sd(x[,-1])*sqrt(252))
##        HS       CSI       STI      N225 
## 0.2048923 0.3974830 0.1166858 0.2532792
all.equal(apply(df[,2:5],2,sd), sapply(df_l,function(x) sd(x[,-1])))
## [1] TRUE

Government Bond Yields

In the below example US Government Rates are downloaded from FRED website using lapply()

library(xts)
library(quantmod)
rate_symbols <- c("DGS1","DGS2","DGS3","DGS5","DGS7","DGS10","DGS20","DGS30")
Rates <- lapply(rate_symbols, function(x) getSymbols(x, src='FRED', auto.assign = FALSE))

Combining the data into one xts object:

Rates <- do.call(cbind.xts,Rates)

Data Manipulation

library(reshape2)
Rates <- data.frame(Date = index(Rates), coredata(Rates), stringsAsFactors = FALSE) 
Rates <- melt(Rates,id.vars = "Date")
Rates$Year <- format(Rates$Date, '%Y')
tail(Rates)

ETFs

Here certain ETFs are downloaded from yahoo finance. From this data the monthly returns will be calculated.

Tickers     <- c("IWM","AGG","TLT","TIP","ILF","HYG","EMB","GSG","ICF","IXC")
ETF_Data   <- sapply(Tickers,
                     function(x) tryCatch(getSymbols(x, auto.assign=FALSE),
                                          error = function(e){print(paste(x,'not found'));NA}),
                     simplify = FALSE,
                     USE.NAMES = TRUE)
